\Gamma(t) = \left(\frac{\tilde s (t)}{\tilde s_0}\right)^{\frac{1}{N}},
\end{align}
for all time. In particular, $\int_0^T q(t) dt = 0$ and $\Gamma(t)$ is uniformly bounded and periodic. Here, $T$ is the period of the system \eqref{qtildessys} (equivalently \eqref{qode},\eqref{sode}).

\label{remAexp}
It is important to note that $A(t)$ is connected to $\eta,w$ only through the initial data, $\eta_0,w_0$. In other words, \eqref{qode}, \eqref{sode}, \eqref{Aode} with initial data $q_0,s_0,A_0$ constitute an IVP independent from the dynamics of \eqref{simplestODE}.

Moreover, $A(t)$ can be explicitly solved for. Also, from Lemma \ref{tildesexpq}, $A(t)$ has the same period as $q,s$.

nodes.proof:
Suppose $A(t)\geq 0$ for all time. At the time $t_0$ where $s$ is maximum, from \eqref{sode} we have $q(t_0)=0$ and,
\begin{align*}
& 0\leq A(t_0) = q(t_0)w(t_0) -k\eta(t_0)s(t_0)  = -k\eta(t_0)s(t_0).
\end{align*}
From Lemma \ref{qslemapp}, $s(t_0)>0$. Hence, $\eta(t_0)\leq 0$. This gives us the existence of a time $t_c>0$ with $t_c\leq t_0$ such that $\eta(t_c)=0$. 

The proof is similar for $A(t)\leq 0$ situation.

