\label{Asign}
Suppose $N\geq 3$. 
\begin{itemize}
    \item If $1+\frac{A_0(N-2)}{k}\leq 0$, then $A(t)<0$ for all $t>0$.
    \item If 

    $\int_0^t q \leq -\frac{1}{N-2}\ln\left( 1+\frac{A_0(N-2)}{k} \right)$ for all $t>0$, then $A(t)\leq 0$ for all $t>0$.
    \item If 

    $\int_0^t q \geq -\frac{1}{N-2}\ln\left( 1+\frac{A_0(N-2)}{k} \right)$ for all $t>0$, then $A(t)\geq 0$ for all $t>0$.
\end{itemize}

nodes.proof:
The first assertion follows from the fact that if $1+\frac{A_0(N-2)}{k}\leq 0$, then from \eqref{Aeq}, $A(t)<0$ for all time.





Note that if $1+\frac{A_0(N-2)}{k}>0$, then it can be readily seen from \eqref{Aeq} that $A(\Gamma)$ has exactly two real roots, $0$ and 
\begin{align}
\label{kappaexp}
\kappa:= \left( 1+ \frac{A_0(N-2)}{k}\right)^{\frac{1}{N-2}}>0.
\end{align} 
Moreover, for nonnegative arguments $\Gamma$ in \eqref{Aeq}, $A(\Gamma)> 0$ for $\Gamma\in (0,\kappa)$ and $A(\Gamma)<0$ for $\Gamma>\kappa$. 

Now suppose the hypothesis of the second assertion holds. Straightforward calculations then imply $\Gamma(t)\geq \kappa$ for all $t$. Therefore, $A(\Gamma)\leq 0$ for all attainable values of $\Gamma$. This proves the second assertion. 

The third assertion is similar, only that here the hypothesis implies $\Gamma(t) \leq \kappa$. Therefore, $A(t)\geq 0$.

