As long as $w\neq 0$, $\tilde w\neq 0$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{d(w- \tilde w)}{dy} & = -kcy\left( \frac{1}{w}-\frac{1}{\tilde w} \right) - (N-1)(q+q_M) +\frac{B}{w} - \frac{B_{min}}{\tilde w}\\
&  = \frac{kcy}{w\tilde w}(w-\tilde w) -(N-1)(q+q_M) - \frac{B}{w\tilde w}(w-\tilde w) + \frac{1}{\tilde w}(B-B_{min}).
\end{align*}
When $\tilde w<0$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{d(w- \tilde w)}{dy} + \frac{B-kcy}{w\tilde w}(w-\tilde w) & = -(N-1)(q+q_M) + \frac{1}{\tilde w}(B-B_{min})\\
& \leq 0.
\end{align*}
Suppose the solution trajectory $(w(y),y)$ touches $(\tilde w(y),y) $ at a point $y=y_c$. Since $\eta'(y_c)=w(y_c)<0$, the trajectory was moving in the negative $Y$ direction. Integrating the above inequality,
\begin{align*}
& w(y_c+\epsilon)-\tilde w(y_c+\epsilon) \leq \left(w(y_c)-\tilde w(y_c)\right) e^{\int_{y_c}^{y_c+\epsilon} \frac{B-kcy}{w\tilde w}dy}.
\end{align*}
From this, 
\begin{align*}
& 0 < w(y_c+\epsilon)-\tilde w(y_c+\epsilon) \leq 0,
\end{align*}
which is a contradiction.

As long as $w\neq 0$, $\tilde w\neq 0$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{d(w- \hat w)}{dy} & = -\frac{ky}{w}\left( c+s(N-1)\right) + \frac{kcy}{N\hat w} + \frac{ke^{-(N-1)\int_0^t q}}{w} - \frac{M}{\hat w} \\
&  = -\frac{ky}{w}\left( c+s(N-1) - \frac{c}{N}\right) - \frac{kcy}{N}\left(\frac{1}{w}-\frac{1}{\hat w}\right)+ \\
& \qquad  \frac{1}{w}\left( ke^{-(N-1)\int_0^t q} -M \right) + M\left(\frac{1}{w}-\frac{1}{\hat w}\right).
\end{align*}
When $w>0$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac{d(w- \hat w)}{dy} + \frac{M-kcy/N}{w\hat w}(w-\hat w) & = -\frac{ky}{w}\left( c+s(N-1) - \frac{c}{N}\right) + \frac{1}{w}\left( ke^{-(N-1)\int_0^t q} -M \right) \\
& \leq 0.
\end{align*}
Suppose the solution trajectory $(w(y),y)$ touches $(\hat w(y),y) $ at a point $y=y_c$. Since $\eta'(y_c)=w(y_c)>0$, the trajectory was moving in the positive $Y$ direction. Integrating the above inequality,
\begin{align*}
& w(y_c)-\hat w(y_c) \leq \left(w(y_c-\epsilon)-\hat w(y_c-\epsilon)\right) e^{\int_{y_c-\epsilon}^{y_c} \frac{M-kcy/N}{w\hat w}dy}.
\end{align*}
From this, 
\begin{align*}
& 0 \leq w(y_c-\epsilon)-\hat w(y_c-\epsilon) < 0,
\end{align*}
which is a contradiction.

The proof for the part that $(w,s)$ never crosses $C_1$ or $C_2$ is very similar to that in the proof of Proposition \ref{propmainwal}. So, we will omit it here. We prove that $s>0$ and $w,s$ remain bounded.

The only points where the trajectory $(w,s)$ could cross the $p$-axis are of the form $(p,0)$ where $p>0$. However, at any such point, $s'>0$ and therefore, the trajectory moves upwards. Consequently, $s(t)>0$ for all $t>0$. As a result,
\begin{align*}
w' & = k - kcs < k. 
\end{align*}
Therefore, $w$ is bounded from above. Moreover,
\begin{align*}
& s' = w - s\psi\ast\rho \leq w,
\end{align*}
and hence, $s$ is bounded from above.

